<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Arab Trade Funding Program (ATFP), an affiliate
of the Abu Dhabi-based Arab Monetary Fund, and Kuwait-Middle East
Bank (KMEP) signed a document under which the former will provide
the latter 20 million U.S. dollars in loan.
</P>
<P>
The loan aims to refund 85 percent of various trade deals
between Kuwait and the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed by ATFP Executive Director and Board
Chairman Jassim al-Manaie and KMEP Board Chairman Saleh Mubarak al-
Fallah.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A recent economic study forcasts the increase of the
Egyptian annual software exports to dlrs 500 million over the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
The current value of exports from this product is estimated at
dlrs 40 million a year.
</P>
<P>
Al-Alam Al-Youm economic daily quoted the study as stating that
the software industry in Egypt involves 1300 foundations where some
10,000 persons are working.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has about 70,000 nationals working in international
software manufacturing companies including 5,000 in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian trade deficit decreased in the period from
July 1999 to January 2000 by LE 3.7 billion (one dollar equals 3.
435 Egyptian pound) to finally register LE 21.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
Al-Alam Al-Youm quoted the monthly report prepared by the
Cabinet Centre for Information and Decision Supporting, as
referring the reasons of this retreat to the increase of the free
zones' exports by LE 1.118 billion and a coinciding decrease in the
bill of imports by LE 3.52 billion.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptians and businessmen expected a thaw in the cash
fluidity crisis and a subsequent gradual recovery of markets over
the next few days. This upbeat tone echoed with the government's
announced pledge to pay off the debts due to the companies. The
debts are estimated at 25 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
Al-Alam al-Youm reported that the businessmen asked the Central
Bank of Egypt to review the percentage of coverage earmarked for
the bond credits so that this might revitalize the import
activities and break the state of stagnation which has been
gripping the markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
