<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Income Tax In UK At 18-year Peak, Says ITEM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Britons are paying a higher
percentage of income in tax than they have since the early 80s,
says an influential team of economists.
</P>
<P>
A report by accountant Ernst &AMP; Young's ITEM club, says that
Britons will pay 105 billion pounds in income tax this year, equal
to almost 13 percent of average household incomes and the highest
level since 1982.
</P>
<P>
In March, British Prime Minister Tony Blair was forced to admit
that because of indirect taxes, the tax burden had increased under
Labor, despite cuts in basic rate income tax.
</P>
<P>
But the ITEM club says direct taxes on individuals have also
risen because tax thresholds have failed to rise in line with
average pay packets, putting more people in the top 40 percent tax
band.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the report will be seized on by the
Opposition Party as evidence that Labor is misleading voters over
tax.
</P>
<P>
But the Treasury said: "It is well known that the tax burden is
now falling. The government has introduced a 10p tax band and cut
basic income tax and corporation tax rates."
</P>
<P>
Because of the working family tax credit, working family are
now better off than when Labor came to power,it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
