<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Discounts Push Rover Sales To 3-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Rover grabbed its biggest share of
the UK car market for over three years in April as sales more than
doubled.
</P>
<P>
Its sales jumped 116 percent last month to 22,665 compared with
10,467 in April 1999, giving it a 13.5 percent share of the market.
</P>
<P>
It was Rover's best April sales performance for 10 years and
its highest market share since December 1996.
</P>
<P>
John Parkinson, managing director of Rover UK, said:"We are
grateful for the support and loyalty expressed, in convincing
fashion, by the British public to Rover."
</P>
<P>
However, market experts said the surge in Rover sales was
driven by an apparent combination of intense marketing incentives
and concern among buyers for the plight of the group.
</P>
<P>
It was less a case of patriotic fervor and more a response to
huge discounts designed to shift stocks, they added.
</P>
<P>
The rise in Rover sales helped British-built cars take 34
percent of the market. But the Society of Motor Manufacturers and
Traders said the trend was unlikely to last because the continuing
weakness of the euro was putting "immense pressure" on British
business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
