<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Kenyan Soldiers Injured in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Eight Kenyan soldiers have been
wounded by rebels in Sierra Leone and 25 others, including a
brigadier and four majors, are being held hostage, Kenyan media
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The figures were disclosed Sunday in the first military
statement on last week's attack on United Nations peacekeepers by
rebels led by Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
Media said that the Sierra Leone rebels were using some 300
captured troops as a human shield and driving in white United
Nations armored carriers as they advanced on the capital,
Freetown.
</P>
<P>
A statement from Kenya's Defence Headquarters for the first
time identified the 33 Kenyan soldiers injured or captured in
Sierra Leone and stated that only two men -- and not four as
reported earlier -- were missing.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has not indicated whether any Kenyan
soldier was killed there.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government is actively engaged in pursuing
diplomatic and other initiatives to ensure the safety and
well-being of the Kenyan troops in Sierra Leone, according to the
statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
