<HEADLINE> Palestinians Reject Israeli Redeployment Map </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator in the
final- status talks Yasser Abed Rabbo on Sunday totally rejected
the Israeli-drawn redeployment maps presented in the Eilat talks.
</P>
<P>
Rabbo made the statement after discussing with U.S. Mideast
peace envoy Dennis Ross in the West Bank the maps and the Israeli-
made obstacles against the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel proposes to hand over to the Palestinians 66 percent of
the West Bank, according to the maps.
</P>
<P>
"The maps can never be a starting point for the final-status
talks," Rabbo said.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on the thorniest issues between Israel and the
Palestinians, namely the fate of Jerusalem, borders, water,
refugees, and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks are going on with the
mediation of Ross and may take a form other than the Eilat talks,
Rabbo told Radio of Palestine, expressing hope that the forthcoming
talks would be more serious.
</P>
<P>
The Eilat talks were adjourned on Saturday. Rabbo, Ross and
Israeli chief negotiator Oded Eran held a tripartite meeting west
Jerusalem on Saturday Evening in an attempt to move the peace talks
forward but no progress was made.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian-Israeli summit is expected to be held Sunday
Evening in the presence of Ross for the same purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
