<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Endorses Tax Reform Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet Sunday endorsed in
principle the tax reform package, which was proposed by a treasury
committee, after a five-hour discussion.
</P>
<P>
The proposals, submitted to Prime Minister Ehud Barak last
Thursday, won the overwhelmingly majority support of 17 cabinet
ministers in a voting.
</P>
<P>
The two abstainers were Labor and Social Affairs Minister Eli
Yishai and Education Minister Yossi Sarid, who both argued that the
budget allocation to implement the tax reform will leave less money
for social reforms.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Finance Ministry Director-General Avi Ben-Bassat, the
major conceiver of the sweeping reform proposals, said the plan
will cost the government tens of millions of Shekels to carry out,
while presenting the recommendations to the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The cost, however, is "marginal" while comparing to the 12
billion Shekels (about 2.92 billion U.S. dollars) of tax revenues
the reform will generate, the director general added.
</P>
<P>
The weekly cabinet meeting also approved a series of interim
orders for preventing speculators from "exploiting the time" gap
between the publication of the reform package and its formal
implementation.
</P>
<P>
It was also decided to create a ministerial committee headed by
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin to supervise the preparation of the
tax reform bill.
</P>
<P>
The committee will hear the ministers' objections regarding the
reform, which had been heard in the past few days, and explore the
possibility of making minor changes in its final embellishment.
</P>
<P>
Most of the ministers generally support the reform, but they
object to some sections of the plan to guard the interests of
respective interests groups they represented.
</P>
<P>
Under the ministerial committee, eight special teams had been
assembled by the Finance Ministry to prepare legislation documents
on the basis of the tax recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations were building in a framework of introducing
25-percent new taxation on capital gains, such as profits from
stock markets and deposits, to lighten the tax burden of average
wage earners.
</P>
<P>
However, it encounters great criticism due to its abolishing of
a half-point tax exemption for working women and its levying on
continued-education funds for workers.
</P>
<P>
But Barak is the most ardent supporter of the proposals, which
will accomplish one of his major pledges he promised during the
general election in last May.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said at Sunday's meeting that the current tax
reform is an historic step by the government, which will impose
reasonable taxes on the capital market and reduce taxes on wage
earners.
</P>
<P>
These people, who leave each morning to work, form the backbone
of every modern economy and pay the main tax burden. Thus, the tax
reform report reflects sensitivity and is an act of social justice,
a statement issued by Barak's office quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The governmental interim orders for implementing the reform will
be rendered to the Knesset (Parliament) Finance Committee for
confirmation on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bill itself is expected to go through its first reading in
the next few months and began to be effective by January 1, 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
