<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian State to Be Declared Before September 13, Qureia Reaffirms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) Ahmed Qureia reaffirmed on Sunday that there is "no
option" for the Palestinians except the declaration of an
independent state before the end of 2,000.
</P>
<P>
"We will declare our state and define its borders with Jerusalem
as its capital," Qureia said during his meeting with Secretary
General of International Parliamentary Union Andres Johnson in al-
Beira, the West Bank, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that an understanding will be reached on this
issue before September 13.
</P>
<P>
The declaration of independence without an agreement with Israel
will mean that a great part of the Palestinians will remain under
the Israeli occupation, Qureia noted. He urged the international
community to put an end to the Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians reject the Israeli claims on the status of
Jerusalem which is part of the Palestinian territories according to
the U.N. resolutions, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
In February the PLC declared determination to establish
Palestinian Statehood by the end of 2,000.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel are scheduled to reach a permanent
peace treaty by September 13 after the settlement of the final
status issues including Jerusalem, the borders, the refugees, water
and the settlements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians consider September 13 the deadline of
unilateral declaration of statehood with or without a permanent
peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Israeli side insists not to hand over or divide
Jerusalem and considers the holy city the "eternal and unified
capital" of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
On the border issue, the Israeli government said it will not
hand over all the West Bank territories where large Jewish
settlements are still in existence.
</P>
<P>
Israeli negotiators offered to the Eilat talks on Friday a map
on boder demarkation that envisages the transfer of 66 percent of
the West Bank to the Palestinian. However, the Palestinians turned
down the offer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
