<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Shin Bet Head Nomination Approved by Israeli Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli cabinet Sunday approved
the appointment of Avaraham Dichter as new Director of Israel's
General Security Service (Shin Bet).
</P>
<P>
Dichter, currently deputy director of the powerful agency, will
be officially promoted to the post next Sunday, a statement issued
after the weekly cabinet meeting announced.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said at the meeting that
Dichter, a 47-year-old official having grown up through ranks in
the internal security agency, has wide experience and knows all its
areas of operations.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister wished him success in the job, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
A former member of the Israel Defense Forces' elite General
Staff Reconnaissance Unit, Dichter joined the Shin Bet in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Firstly as a bodyguard, he rose step by step and was finally
named as head of the bodyguard unit following the assassination of
former prime minister Yitzhak Rabin, which revealed the agency's
flawed structure.
</P>
<P>
Dichter then served as commander of the southern region of Shin
Bet and later head of training in the Arab Affairs Branch. He was
named deputy of the outgoing director Ami Ayalon last November.
</P>
<P>
Barak Sunday also praised the contribution to the country by
Ayalon, a former Israeli Navy commander who took over his current
post at a difficult time in the wake of the assassination of Rabin
and the wave of terrorist bombings in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Barak stated that Ayalon, who has served for the past four
years, succeeded in his job in an exemplary manner, putting the
Shin Bet back on its feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
