<HEADLINE> US Envoy Mediates for Barak-Arafat Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. special Mideast envoy
Dennis Ross met Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Sunday to
bridge wide gaps btween Israel and the Palestinians over the scope
of an emerging Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place ahead of a planned summit later Sunday
between Barak and Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Barak and Arafat are to discuss Israel's delayed handover of
three Palestinian suburbs of Jerusalem, Jewish settlement expansion
in the West Bank and other issues to be resolved in the treaty,
including Palestinian statehood, Palestinian officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials had said that Ross will sit in on the meeting
scheduled for Sunday night, but U.S. embassy spokesman Larry
Schwartz said later that Ross will not attend.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Palestinians rejected an Israeli proposal for interim
statehood in 66 percent of the West Bank and Gaza Strip in exchange
for postponing negotiations over final borders and the Jerusalem
issue. They fear that if such measures are adopted, negotiations
over the pending issues may drag on for years in the absence of
international pressure.
</P>
<P>
Barak had earlier indicated the willingness to transfer three
villages on the outskirts of Jerusalem, Abu Dis, Azariye and
Swahara, to full Palestinian control as a goodwill gesture prior to
the final Israeli troops withdrawal from the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, which is slated for June. But he later delayed the handover
in the face of opposition from hardliners inside his coalition.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian and Israeli negotiators started a new round of
negotiations on April 30 in the Israeli Red Sea resort city of
Eilat to discuss issues related to the third redeployment and the
outlining of a final status agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived to mediate the peace talks last Wednesday, is
to return to Washington Monday after more talks with negotiators.
</P>
