<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tourism Affected by Negative Publicity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The negative publicity Zimbabwe is
receiving abroad continues to affect the tourism industry
especially in the major resort of Victoria Falls where hotel
bookings have dropped by between 60 and 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rudy Boribon, general manager of a tourism company called
"Touch the Wild Private Limited", Sunday told the Zimbabwe News
Agency that the drop in tourist arrivals was mainly due to the
picture of insecurity that was being put across by consular travel
 advisors who were picking things from foreign media which were
biased.
</P>
<P>
"Tourists are concerned about their safety when travelling and
they put much emphasis on taking insurance but these are only
given out depending on how safe a country is regarded to be," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Boribon said the drop was first experienced during the fuel
shortage that hit the country late last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mines, Environment and Tourism Minister Simon Moyo
has expressed optimism that the difficulties being faced by the
country were a passing phase.
</P>
<P>
He said the difficulties could be a blessing in disguise for
marketers of tourism in the country because most people around
the world knew something about Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Tourism arrivals had grown by 8 percent from 2.09 million in
1998 to 2. 25 million in 1999 but these were likely to decline
drastically this year.
</P>
<P>
Tourism contributes to about 7 percent of the country's Gross
Domestic Product. 
</P>
