<HEADLINE> China's Silicon Valley to Earn 600 billion yuan By 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Sales from Zhongguancun Science and
Technology Park in Beijing, known as China's "Silicon Valley", is
expected to grow 20 percent annually to 600 billion yuan by 2010,
according to a senior Beijing official.
</P>
<P>
The Park has more than 6,600 high-tech companies, including
domestic companies such as Legend, Stone and Founder as well as
over 1,000 foreign-funded companies such as IBM and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
Zhongguancun Park has become a new economic growth point of
Beijing, said Vice-Mayor Liu Zhihua at the Second Annual Session
of International Businessmen Advisory Conference to the Mayor of
Beijing, which opened today.
</P>
<P>
Last year, sales hit 86.4 billion yuan, sales from software and
related services accounting for more than 40 percent. According to
a target approved by the State Council, the Park will become a
first-class international science and technology center in ten
years.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that Zhongguancun Park will focus on software industry
and information service while developing related sectors such as
risk investment, trade in high technology and educational training.
</P>
</TEXT>
