<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Began Deliberation on Tax Reform Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet Sunday began its
deliberation on the tax reform recommendations proposed by an
Israeli treasury committee last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the weekly cabinet meeting, the government is
expected to endorse the sweeping tax reform package in principle,
approve interim orders to implement the reform immediately, and
render these orders to the Knesset (Parliament) Finance Committee
on Monday for confirmation, source in Prime Minister's Office said.
</P>
<P>
Avi Ben-Bassat, Director General of the Finance Ministry, and
other committee members presented their recommendations to the
cabinet ministers before they began discussion.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Bassat, the major conceiver of the committee report,
revealed at the presentation remarks that the reform plan will cost
the government tens of millions of Shekels to carry out.
</P>
<P>
But comparing to the 12 billion Shekels (about 2.92 billion U.S.
dollars) of tax revenues the reform will generate, the cost is "
marginal", Ben-Bassat added.
</P>
<P>
The Ben-Bassat committee was established eight months ago to
accomplish Prime Minister Ehud Barak's election pledges to
correct "historic income tax distortions."
</P>
<P>
It recommended last Thursday that a 25-percent tax should be
levied on real profits made from stock trading, short-and medium-
term interest-bearing savings plans, and continued-education funds.
</P>
<P>
The taxation is aimed to offset the state's loss of tax revenue
due to income tax reform, in which the take-home pay of middle-
class wage earners will be increased.
</P>
<P>
The reform plan garnered general support from a decisive
majority of ministers. However, most of them issued their
reservations to certain articles in the proposal, guarding the
interests of respective interest groups they represent.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's cabinet session is to provide a platform for these
ministers to express their opinion more openly, which the Finance
Ministry promised to take into account in its further burnishing of
the report, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The most criticized sections of the recommendations are the
abolishment of a half-point tax exemption of working women and the
taxation of continued-education funds of average workers.
</P>
<P>
The Histadrut, or Jewish Labor Federation, organized a one-
hour "warning strike" against the taxation of continued-education
funds on Sunday morning, involving about 1.5 million employees from
Israel Radio, Israel Electric, Ports, Airports and Railway
Authorities, banks, and government offices throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Histadrut leader Amir Peretz said the work stoppage was just the
first step against the tax reform, which he claimed contains "land
mines and traps" for low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
In a related front, Israel's High Court had order the finance
minister to submit explanations by 5 p.m. Sunday (0200 GMT) to
justify its administrative order to block the banks to open new
saving plans.
</P>
<P>
The order, issued by Finance Minister Avraham Shohat last
Thursday, was to prevent investors from "exploiting the time" gap
between the publication of the reform package to its formal
implementation, which will impose a 25-percent tax to the deposits.
</P>
<P>
However, Knesset member Avigdor Lieberman appealed to the High
Court last Friday, asking it to nullify the order, which he argued
is against Savings Encouragement Law and Basic Law: Freedom of
Occupation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Finance Minister had assembled eight special
teams to prepare legislation on the basis of the tax
recommendations, which is expected to go through its first reading
in the next few months and began to be effective by January 1,
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
