<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tensions Mounting as Rebels March Onto S. Leone's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Tensions are mounting in the capital
Freetown of the war-torn Sierra Leone as reports claimed that the
rebels of the country, who allegedly held hostage of about 500
United Nations peacekeepers, marched onto the capital, sources
reaching here said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Philip Winslow, United Nations spokesman in Freetown, was
quoted as saying that the rebels had advanced towards the capital
in defiance of the peace agreement signed last year by the
government and the rebels in Lome, capital of Togo.
</P>
<P>
However, Winslow retracted earlier U.N. statements that the
rebel were on the outskirts of the capital which caused U.N. and
foreign aid workers to take refuge in hotel for possible
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
Fighting between U.N. peacekeepers and the rebels on Saturday
was confirmed by U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
Reports of the rebel advance towards the capital revived
memories of a bloody battle in January 1999 when a Nigerian-led
West African intervention force prevented rebels from taking the
city. An estimated 5,000 people died in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials said about 300 U.N. peacekeepers or civilian
support staff had been held hostages by the rebels and another 200
U.N. soldiers had been lost contact.
</P>
<P>
However, a joint statement issued Saturday in Freetown claimed
that the rebels and the U.N. peacekeeping force had agreed to send
a joint mission on Sunday to areas where the hostages allegedly
held.
</P>
<P>
The progress was made after the Saturday talks between the
rebel leader Foday Sankoh and special representative Oluyemi
Adeniji of the U.N. secretary-general for Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"Both parties showed a high level of understanding and
responsibility to push the peace process forward," said the
statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
