<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak: Pullout Not to Affect Fighting Cross-Border Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
said here Sunday that the withdrawal from south Lebanon will not
affect Israel's capability to retaliate any cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the cabinet that the government is ready to provide
more economic assistance to the residents of the confrontation line
along the northern border.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet met Sunday to discuss recent developments in the
north, particularly the tense situation following Hezbollah's
rocket attacks last weekend against northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Hezbollah, or Party of God, fired 40 Katyusha
rockets on northern Israel and 20 of them landed at Israel's
norther border town of Kiryat Shmona, killing one Israeli solider
and wounding 25 others.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh warned the Syrians on
Sunday against backing Hezbollah to conduct military activities
against northern Israel. Israel will retaliate sharper against any
such activities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sneh also said the defense ministry is requesting the government
to allocate some 35 million shekels (about 8.75 million U.S.
dollars) in the near future as special funds to help the northern
residents to cope with the economic and security problems.
</P>
<P>
This allocation will be part of the 450 million U.S. dollars the
government prepared for the northern residents to cope with
economic and security problem after Israel's pullout from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Among the items in the aid package is a 76.25 million U.S.
dollar program to build alternative roads to those abutting the
border.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of residents of Kiryat Shmona demonstrated in the
town's center on Sunday, calling on the government to improve
economic and security conditions.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators burnt tires on the main road through the town,
saying the government should take stronger action in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In the last two days, situation in northern Israel has turned to
normal as Hezbollah and Israel exercised restraint and no exchange
fire was reported so far.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, backed by Iran and Syria, is the main military group
in Lebanon fighting against Israeli occupation which started 22
years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
