<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arsenic Level Alarming in Bangladesh's Drinking Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Arsenic level in drinking water
sources reached a dangerous mark in 918 villages of Bangladesh,
according to a study released here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by researchers of Dhaka Community Hospital
and the School of Environmental Studies of India's Jadavpur
University, claimed that Bangladesh's arsenic calamity was one of
the most virulent throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The researchers analyzed 22,003 tube well water samples from 64
districts in the country, and their results in five years up to
February, 2000 showed that arsenic level in ground water was above
0.01 mg per liter in 54 out of the 64 districts, and in 47
districts it was above 0.05 mg per liter.
</P>
<P>
A total of 918 villages have been identified to be above the 0.
05-mg-per-liter level.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said that so far they had analyzed around 11,
000 hair, nail, urine and skin-scale samples from affected
villages, and over 90 percent of the people tested arsenic
positive in their hair, nail and urine.
</P>
<P>
Of the 17,896 people examined at random from the affected
villages, 3,688 tested skin-lesion positive, the study report said.
</P>
<P>
The researchers feared that it was only the tip of an iceberg
of the actual calamity.
</P>
<P>
"The more we survey, the more we find people suffering from
arsenic skin lesion," they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
