<HEADLINE> Putin Pledges to Consolidate Russian Society  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin,
who was officially sworn in earlier Sunday, said his work will be
guided exclusively by state interests.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the solemn inauguration ceremony at
the Kremlin, Putin thanked the Russians for supporting him in the
March 26 elections and pledged to "ensure that the leaders elected
by the people defend their interests in and outside Russia."
</P>
<P>
"This is the cardinal position which I did and will defend,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"I assure you that in my work I will be guided exclusively by
the state interests. Maybe, I will fail to avoid mistakes. But I
promise to work openly and honestly," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
"Every day and every hour we must remember that we are one
nation and we have a common future," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
Putin, who was born on October 7, 1952 in Leningrad (now St.
Petersburg), was elected in the March 26 presidential balloting
with a vote of about 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration ceremony was broadcast live by the country's
three major television channels.
</P>
<P>
Putin's predecessor Boris Yeltsin, who stepped down on New
Year's Eve, about six months before the expiry of his term, was
present at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Appearing fit and energetic, Yeltsin congratulated Putin,
wished him success and asked him to "take care of Russia and
protect it."
</P>
<P>
