CHIANG MAI, Thailand, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government
will contribute 10 billion yen (92.5 million U.S. dollars) for
setting up a fund within the Asian Development Bank (ADB) for
poverty reduction to support the bank's fight against poverty,
Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa announced here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at the 33rd Annual Meeting of the Board of
Governors of the ADB, Miyazawa said the fund aims to provide
grants in relation to the bank's loans to reduce poverty and also
to support capacity-building efforts.
</P>
<P>
"By drawing upon this fund, we hope that the bank's loans for
poverty reduction will become even more effective," he said.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with the bank's strategy of refocusing on its work
with the overarching goal of eliminating poverty from the region,
he expects that the strategy will be translated into day-to-day
operations of the bank to support those who could not fully
benefit from economic growth in the past.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee the successful implementation of the poverty
reduction strategy, Miyazawa said the bank should conduct a
continuous dialogue -- not only with governments in the developing
countries but also with other stakeholders, including the members
of civil society at large.
</P>
<P>
He urged the ADB to enhance coordination with the World Bank
and bilateral aid agencies, strengthen the capacity of its
organization as well as that of its own staff, and implement
measures to promote the sense of ownership in the developing
countries, to expand poverty related database and to reinforce its
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
Miyazawa also talked about the future role of the ADB and the
need for a long-term strategy for the future.
</P>
<P>
He said the crises in the emerging economies have prompted a
heated debate about the reform of the International Monetary Fund
and the World Bank and other international financial institutions,
and how their functions should be adjusted to the changing world
economy.
</P>
<P>
"Reform of the World Bank, in particular, will have significant
implications on the bank, its partner for Asian development," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the ADB to seriously consider how to respond, as
a regional bank, to the decentralization of the World Bank, what
role it should play in supporting the emerging market countries
with the access to the international capital markets and how it
can provide more active and effective support to private sector
development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, focusing on poverty reduction, opened on Saturday
in this mountainous city, some 1,000 kilometers north of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 representatives from most of the bank's 58 members,
including finance ministers, central bank governors and officials
from banks and international financial institutions, are attending
the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Governors, the ADB's highest policy-making body,
comprises one representative from each member and meets annually.
</P>
<P>
The board elects the Board of Directors every two years.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the bank is also holding seminars on issues
ranging from poverty reduction and the international financial
architecture to the global networked economy.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1966, the ADB is a multinational finance
institution. With 42 of its members from the Asian and Pacific
region, the bank engages in a wide range of social and economic
development activities aimed at improving the welfare of the
people in the region.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the ADB rededicated itself to the fight against
poverty by adopting a new poverty reduction strategy that rests on
three pillars: pro-poor, sustainable economic growth, social
development and good governance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
