<HEADLINE> Cambodia Starts Pilot Demobilization Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPOT, Cambodia, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A total of 128 soldiers
were demobilized Sunday at a discharge center in Kampot province
under Cambodia's pilot demobilization project.
</P>
<P>
It was the first batch of the 250 military personnel to be
discharged from the army in Kampot. The second batch of 122 will
be demobilized in four days.
</P>
<P>
Present at Sunday's inauguration of the Pilot Demobilization
Program were Sok An, minister of the Council of Ministers and
chairman of the Council for the Demobilization of Armed Forces (
CDAF), Tea Banh and Sisowath Sirirath, co-ministers of National
Defense, diplomats, as well as representatives from international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces personnel to be demobilized are from a special
target group, comprising chronically ill soldiers, disabled,
elderly and some regular forces. Most of those to be demobilized
are no longer in the barracks and have already returned to their
respective community.
</P>
<P>
According General Secretary of the CDAF Svay Sitha, of the 250
soldiers, 26 are female, 69 are disabled, 47 are chronically ill
and 30 are elderly.
</P>
<P>
Each demobilized soldier got the government cash allowances of
Cambodian riel equivalent to 240 U.S. dollars, as well as other
kinds of assistance including 150 kilograms of rice, canned fish,
salt and cooking oil which were contributed by the U.N. World Food
Program, and some items of the household kits provided by Germany.
</P>
<P>
Some discharged soldiers told reporters that they supported the
government's demobilization program. "We are looking forward to
being ordinary people after the country has a complete peace
environment. It is good for our country as well as ourselves,"
said one of them called Sam Som. But some others worried that they
would lead a harder life with so litter money.
</P>
<P>
After the discharge ceremony, the 128 discharged soldiers and
their families were transported to the communities where they
chose to settle down.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,500 soldiers will be demobilized in four provinces
under the pilot program. After Kampot, Kampong Thom will discharge
460 soldiers from May 16 to May 22, to be followed by Banteay
Meanchey which is to demobilize 370 soldiers from June 12 to 17
and Battambang which will demobilize 420 soldiers from June 22 to
the end of that month.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a total of 31,500 soldiers will be
demobilized beginning this year until 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
