<HEADLINE> Profile: Russian President Vladimir Putin  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Vladimir Putin was sworn in as
Russia's new president in a ceremony at the Kremlin on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Born on October 7, 1952, in Leningrad, now St. Petersburg,
Putin was the only child of a factory foreman and his wife who
were both reportedly decorated war veterans.
</P>
<P>
He was enrolled in martial arts classes by his parents. By 16,
he was a top-ranked expert at sambo, a Russian combination of judo
and wrestling dating from the 1930's. He was Leningrad's judo
champion in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Putin entered School 281, an elite college-preparatory
institution where only students with near-perfect grades could get
in.
</P>
<P>
As he was finishing his studies as a law student at Leningrad
State University, Putin was approached by a professional recruiter
for the KGB. Shortly after, he started an about 16-year career
with the intelligence establishment. Putin was the only one picked
up by the KGB of the 100 or more students in the class of 1975 in
the Leningrad law school.
</P>
<P>
Besides the law degree, Putin also has a doctorate in
economics from Russia's oldest technical university. He speaks
some English and such impressive German that he can imitate
dialects.
</P>
<P>
Putin returned to Leningrad from Germany in the early 1990s
and took up work in the international affairs department at his
alma mater. He later became a first deputy governor of Leningrad
under his mentor, Anatoly Sobchak, handling all foreign trade and
business in the second largest Russian city.
</P>
<P>
He was praised as "one of the more honest and decent people in
the St. Petersburg government" and credited for significant
foreign investment projects there in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, when Sobchak lost his political campaign, Putin
resigned from the city government and later moved to Moscow to
work in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
In July 1998, he was appointed head of the Federal Security
Service, the main successor to the KGB. In March 1999 his duties
were expanded to include running the Kremlin Security Council, a
top advisory body that includes ministers of the so-called power
ministries.
</P>
<P>
Five months later, he was handpicked by then President Boris
Yeltsin to become the country's fifth prime minister in about 18
months. Then, he became acting president after Yeltsin's abrupt
resignation on December 31.
</P>
<P>
Putin's tough-guy image and forceful, no-nonsense style, as
displayed in handling Chechnya, won him mounting support among
Russians who are frustrated by the chaos and the woes accumulated
over the years since the disintegration of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Many pin their hopes on the young and energetic Putin to lift
Russia from the ashes, and restore the national pride.
</P>
<P>
Putin is married, with two teenage daughters. He does not
smoke, rarely drinks, and regularly works 16 to 17 hours a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
