<HEADLINE> mee050702hke --- Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Lebanese government has raised a potential obstacle to
Israel's proposal to withdrawal from the security zone in south
Lebanon by demanding Israel also to withdraw from the region of
Sheba village, about 16 kilometers east of Metulla, the foothills
of Mount Hermon.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the area has not been considered Lebanese territory,
but rather, part of it might be conceded to Syria as part of a
peace agreement with Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon is apparently making the demand on the insistence of the
Syrians, who are opposed to Israel's plans for a unilateral
withdrawal. According to diplomatic sources, if the condition is
not met, Lebanon will consider the withdrawal incomplete.
</P>
<P>
Ha'arez
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli government is to authorize transitional
regulations on Sunday to implement a sweeping tax reform based on
the report by the Treasury's Ben-Bassat Commission. The regulations
will be presented to the Knesset's (parliament's) Finance Committee
on Monday for confirmation.
</P>
<P>
A decisive majority of ministers is expected to confirm the
Finance Ministry's formal request to authorize the interim orders.
</P>
<P>
If the tax-reform proposal is approved by the government and the
committee later this year, taxes on various savings plans would go
into effect retroactively from Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat are expected to meet in the next
few days to advance the talks on the final status arrangement and
the third redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Barak will not submit to the cabinet on Monday his proposal to
transfer full control of Palestinian towns near Jerusalem as a "
down payment" on the third redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will discuss ways to overcome difficulties in
their negotiations, which, according to chief Palestinian
negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo, have made "no progress whatsoever".
</P>
<P>
The talks will resume Sunday at a closed location in the
Jerusalem area.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israeli army and civilians in the north are frustrated by
the government's self-restraint from retaliating Hezbollah's rocket
attacks.
</P>
<P>
There have been arguments that the escalation of conflicts would
have only served Hezbollah and Syria. Nevertheless, a clear threat
to Syrian interests is the only way Israel can retain an "effective
deterrent" against attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Defence Force would have hit Syrian military camps
in Lebanon and the economic projects from which Syrian workers make
a living a long time ago, had it not feared a second front in an
all-out war with Syria. 
</P>
