<HEADLINE> Turkish Minister to Visit Syria to Strengthen Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish State Minister Recep Onal,
leading a delegation of 100 businessmen, is due to be in Damascus
on Sunday to strengthen relations between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The visit is part of Ankara's diplomatic drive aimed at
improving cold or disputed relations with neighboring countries,
reported the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Syria have been up in arms against one another for 15
years due to the issue of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
leader Abdullah Ocalan, and at one point in 1998 they drew back
from the brink of war.
</P>
<P>
With the resolution of the thorny Ocalan issue, both the two
countries have expressed interest in improving the lukewarm ties.
In March this year, Turkish Deputy Foreign Ministry Undersecretary
Ugur Ziyal visited Damascus.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day visit, Onal will attend Turkey-Syria Joint
Economic Commission meetings, which will be held after an interval
of 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Agreements on reciprocal encouragement, protection of
investments and cooperation in customs are expected to be signed.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will take up the issue of prevention of double
taxation in the second round of negotiations, according to Turkish
officials.
</P>
<P>
Onal is expected to be received by Prime Minister Mohammed
Mustafa Miro and to have meetings with a number of Syrian
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Turkish officials said that oil is the most important item in
the trade between Syria and Turkey and trade volume either
decreased or increased as a result of the change of the oil deal. A
Turkish Export Product Fair, which will be opened in Damascus in
the middle of May, will provide an opportunity to diversify the
bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Turkey sold goods worth 232 million U.S. dollars to
Syria and imported 307 million dollars of goods from it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
