<HEADLINE> Zambia to Rearm Police to Combat Crime Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is to import
modern and sophisticated firearms for police services to help
combat the escalating crime wave in the country, Inspector General
of Police Sailus Ngangula has disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Times of Zambia newspaper quoted Ngangula as saying
discussions were underway to order versatile guns which were not
only sophisticated, but portable and suitable for police duties.
</P>
<P>
The inspector general who was addressing police officers in
Kabwe in Central Province on Saturday that his men were on the
war-path and would not spare bandits who were robbing and killing
innocent people in cold blood.
</P>
<P>
He said his command had taken time to advise people from
engaging in criminal activities, but the situation still remained
bad.
</P>
<P>
Although ever more and more community police posts are
springing up all over residential, business or industrial and
other areas, the crime situation has steadily got out of hand with
aggravated robbery ranking uppermost.
</P>
<P>
According to police statistics, up to 126,631 crimes were
reported in 1999 and 121,613 in 1998, of which 30,736 and 30,804
convictions were recorded respectively.
</P>
<P>
Of these cases, only 47,474 and 50,693 were investigated and
cleared respectively in 1999 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ngangula said police officers had been killed and his command
has instructed officers to be tough and employ measures to keep
away criminals in case of attack.
</P>
<P>
He described fighting crime as a war, saying that officers
could only fight crime if morale was high and promotions would be
enhanced while logistics would be improved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
