<HEADLINE> Seoul, Washington, Tokyo Agree on Inter-Korean Summit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Seoul, Washington and Tokyo hold no
different opinion on the inter-Korean summit slated in Pyongyang
on June 12-14, South Korean Presidential spokesman Park Joon-
youngthe said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"South Korea, the United States and Japan have agreed the
engagement policy, and have no different opinion in maintaining
and developing it," Park said.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation among the three nations is steadfast and such
cooperation has played a role in working out an agreement on the
opening of the summit, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Park's remarks came after Japanese media reports said that
South Korea and the United States are in discord on the
forthcoming inter-Korean summit, which was agreed by delegates
from both Seoul and Pyongyang in Beijing in early April this year.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also quoted U.S. Ambassador to Seoul Stephen
Bosworth's remarks at a TV program last Saturday as saying that
the summit between South Korean President Kim Dae-jung and
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) leader Kim Jong-il
will have a far-reaching historic significance.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is also closely cooperating with China and Russia
as before, added the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Monday, delegates from Seoul and Pyongyang will hold their
fourth preparatory meeting for the summit at the truce village of
Pammunjom.
</P>
<P>
In the past three meetings which were said "very positive and
pragmatic," the two sides said they have narrowed their
differences on the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
