<HEADLINE> Putin Sworn in as New Russian President  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Vladimir Putin was sworn in as
Russia's new president in an official ceremony in the Kremlin
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Putin, who was born on October 7, 1952 in Leningrad (now St.
Petersburg), was elected in the March 26 presidential election
with a vote of about 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration ceremony was broadcast live by the country's
three major television channels.
</P>
<P>
With his right hand on the text of the Constitution, Putin
vowed "to respect and protect the rights and freedoms of man and
citizen, to observe and protect the Constitution of the Russian
Federation, to protect the sovereignty and independence, security
and integrity of the state and to serve the people faithfully."
</P>
<P>
Putin's predecessor Boris Yeltsin, who stepped down on New
Year's Eve, about six months before the expiry of his term, was
present at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Appearing fit and energetic, Yeltsin congratulated Putin,
wished him success and asked him to "take care of Russia and
protect it."
</P>
<P>
In his brief speech, Putin thanked the Russians for their
support in the elections and promised to work hard, to be guided
by the interests of the motherland and to transform Russia into a
"free, prosperous, strong and civilized" country.
</P>
<P>
Members of both houses of parliament, judges of the
Constitutional court, former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
the wives of Yeltsin and Putin, religious leaders and the heads of
diplomatic missions attended the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
