<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fights Against Water Shortage (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Each morning at dawn, about
thirty residents in Moshanzi Village in north China's Hebei
Province gather around a small water tower to fetch water.
</P>
<P>
Because of a drought, water is a scarce commodity. According to
statistics, many areas, including Moshanzi Village have been
drought-stricken.
</P>
<P>
China's water per capita are about 2,400 cubic meters, making
up 25 percent of the world's average. The United Nations has
listed China among the 13 nations in the world with water
shortages.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 70 percent of water is used for irrigation in
China, but only 40 percent of the irrigation water is efficiently
used due to backward technology. Around 27 million ha of fields
are hit by drought each year. Even when rain is abundant, 30
billion ha of fields lack water.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has adopted water-saving methods on
plains in the northern parts of the country. In the past few years,
25 billion yuan (about three billion US dollars) has been used in
building water-saving irrigation systems in 18 million ha of
fields in 300 counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
