<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pudong Development Changes Residents' Life (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- For most of her life, He Ziping, a
69-year old woman, had lived in a dilapidated house in Pudong in
east Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"Before Pudong was developed, nine people of my family lived
together in a crowded room only 24 square meters large," the
elderly woman recalled. "When it rained, water would leak into our
room through the roof."
</P>
<P>
"Now we have moved into a spacious 100-square-meter house. Gas
has replaced coal for cooking," she said. "There is also a
bathroom in the suite, while in the past we had to share public
washrooms with others."
</P>
<P>
After He settled down in her new surroundings, she went back to
take a look at her previous residence in Pudong's Lujiazui
District, but all she could see was Jinmao Tower, China's highest
skyscraper. "Pudong is changing so fast," she said.
</P>
<P>
Lujiazui has the largest number of foreign financial
institutions in the country. Many foreign employees have settled
down in the Pudong New Area, replete with community service
facilities.
</P>
<P>
China started developing Pudong on April 18, 1990 in a drive to
reinvigorate Shanghai as an international trade and financial
center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
