<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fights Against Water Shortage (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Water is also scarce in cities. About 300 of all 570 cities in
China face water shortage. In the past 50 years, industrialization
and urbanization has seen China's GDP increase tenfold. This has
also seen a substantial increase in water consumption.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shucheng, minister of Water Resources, said at a recent
seminar in Beijing that saving water resources is a priority to
ensure that China's sustainable economic growth will continue.
</P>
<P>
The government will also improve the management of water
sources and employ sophisticated technology to improve water usage,
while issuing new laws and regulations for the safeguarding water
resources.
</P>
<P>
Today around two billion cubic meters of water is saved in
cities and 60 percent of industry-used water are recycled, up 15
percent from the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
However, specialists said that severe water shortages will
still remain a serious problem for China's sustainable economic
development. China's population might reach 1.6 billion by 2030.
By then, water resource per capita is expected to further decrease
by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The northern part of the country has more abundant water. The
government is considering building large projects to transport
water from the Yangtze River to help the regions north of the
Yellow River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
