<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak, Arafat to Meet to Advance Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat are expected to meet on Sunday
or Monday to try to iron out key differences in negotiations for
the framework of a permanent status agreement.
</P>
<P>
Barak's office on Sunday would not rule out the possibility of
the meeting, but gave no details.
</P>
<P>
Other sources here said the two leaders will discuss during the
meeting ways to overcome the difficulties in their negotiations in
light of the expected delay in reaching the framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
The framework agreement was re-scheduled to be signed by the end
of May, and it now seems that this will be further postponed until
June or July.
</P>
<P>
Barak will also try to explain his proposal for the transfer of
three Palestinian villages near Jerusalem, including Abu Dis, to
the Palestinian National Authority as a "territorial down payment."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the current round of the intensive Israeli-
Palestinian final-status talks, which started April 30 at Israel's
southern resort city of Eilat, will resume on Sunday at a closed
location in the Jerusalem area.
</P>
<P>
Chief Palestinian negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo has said that "no
progress whatsoever" had been made in the talks and that the gaps
were still wide.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, the Israeli side has proposed for an interim
Palestinian statehood in 66 percent of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
in exchange for postponing negotiations over final borders and the
Jerusalem issue beyond next September.
</P>
<P>
But this proposal has been rejected by the PNA.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian side refuses completely all Israeli attempts to
avoid international land for peace resolutions...The Israeli
suggestions will be rejected by the Palestinian leadership and will
not be considered for negotiations," the PNA said in a statement
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians fear that if such interim measures are adopted,
negotiations over the remaining issues may then drag on for years
in the absence of international pressure.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross, who is here
mandating the final-status talks, held talks Friday night with
Arafat in the West Bank city of Ramallah after a Thursday meeting
with Barak.
</P>
<P>
Ross will fly back to Washington on Tuesday to report the talks
to U.S. President Bill Clinton and return to the region next week.
</P>
<P>
The final-status talks cover the thorniest issues such as the
fate of Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, borders, Jewish
settlements and water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
