<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke050714--China Urges ADB to Reduce or Exempt Interest Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHIANG MAI, Thailand, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government
hopes that the Asian Development Bank (ADB) will allocate some
resources for ordinary capital resources (OCR) interests payment
reduction or exemption so as to alleviate the burdens of the
borrowers, Chinese Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng said here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 33rd Annual Meeting of the Board of Governors
of the ADB, Xiang said that China hopes that the bank will, in
accordance with its annual review of the net income, allocate some
resources for OCR interests payment reduction or exemption so as
to alleviate the burdens of the borrowers.
</P>
<P>
After hardening the lending terms of soft loans, the ADB has
recently increased the price of OCR, or hard loans, thus placing
more burdens on the borrowers and "seriously hampering the
effectiveness of the bank's strategy for poverty reduction." Xiang
said.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that the ADB will mobilize all possible resources
for more hard loans so as to help the developing members to
realize their objective of poverty reduction, he said.
</P>
<P>
Xiang also appeals to the developed countries to effectively
fulfill their commitment to assisting the poor countries in their
economic development by increasing their contributions to the
Asian Development Fund and concessional funds for technical
assistance for the developing countries in their economic endeavor
for complete elimination of poverty.
</P>
<P>
"From a long-term perspective and the mutual inter-dependence
of the world economy, the economic development of the developing
countries is not only in their own interests, but is also
beneficial to the developed countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concerns at the ADB's income and resource
situation, saying it "leaves no room for optimism."
</P>
<P>
"To turn around this situation, it's necessary for the bank to
further improve its investment management, reduce cost and improve
the quality of project implementation while starting an overall
review of its resource situation at an early date," he said.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the ADB, the most important regional financial
institution for development, for its unremitting efforts to
promote economic development and cooperation for the members of
the Asian region for many years in the past.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the ADB will as always continue to foster
economic growth and cooperation in the region as its fundamental
purpose," said Xiang.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed the participants on China's macroeconomic
situation and the development strategy to speed up development of
its western region, adding that the Chinese government welcomes
the ADB's participation in and support for the development of the
western region of the country, and also welcomes foreign
investment and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, focusing on poverty reduction, opened on Saturday
in this mountainous city, some 1,000 kilometers north of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 representatives from most of the bank's 58 members,
including finance ministers, central bank governors and officials
from international financial institutions, are attending the three-
day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Governors, the ADB's highest policy-making body,
comprises one representative from each member and meets annually.
</P>
<P>
The board elects the Board of Directors every two years.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the bank also holds seminars on issues
ranging from poverty reduction and the international financial
architecture to the global networked economy.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1966, the ADB is a multinational finance
institution.
</P>
<P>
With 42 of its members from the Asian and Pacific region, the
bank engages in a wide range of social and economic development
activities aimed at improving the welfare of the people in the
region.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the ADB rededicated itself to the fight against
poverty by adopting a new poverty reduction strategy that rests on
three pillars: pro-poor, sustainable economic growth, social
development and good governance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
