<HEADLINE> Philippine Negotiator Asks Troops to Stay Away From Hostage-Takers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government chief
negotiator Nur Misuari Sunday called on the military again to stop
troops from drawing near the hostage-takers in Sulu, saying it
could endanger the lives of the foreign captives.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, governor of the Autonomous Region of the Muslim
Mindanao, made the call in Mindanao after his emissaries lost
contact with the Abu Sayyaf men holding 21 foreign hostages in the
mountains of Sulu province, according to the Philippine News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
"My emissaries are still searching for the abductors because
after soldiers clashed with them, they have moved somewhere (from
their former hideout)," Misuari said.
</P>
<P>
The military clashed with the Sayyaf gunmen in Sulu after they
cordoned off the hostage-takers' lair in the hinterlands of
Talipao town.
</P>
<P>
"I was told by my emissaries that the Abu Sayyaf split into
groups and we never really know their exact location at this time
but they must be within Talipao area," he said.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were taken by the Abu Sayyaf to Sulu from the
Malaysian island resort of Sipadan off Borneo two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sulu-based Abu Sayyaf extremists threatened anew
to execute two of their hostages unless the military stop
harassing them and withdraw from the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
