<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Enact New Laws to Check Cyber Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The government of Bangladesh is
expected to enact new laws during the next session of parliament
to check cyber-crimes, the Financial Express reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a high-ranking official at the Science and
Technology Ministry as saying that the Bangladesh Computer Council
(BCC), the government's watchdog on compute-related issues, has
already been asked to examine cyber-laws in the developed
countries to make a draft law.
</P>
<P>
According to rough estimates, there are around 150,000 Internet
users in the country at present. But those directly related to
cyber-crimes are still quite few in numbers.
</P>
<P>
It was not until recently that cyber-crimes have become a hot
topic of discussion and have raised public alarm in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Although at present cyber-crime is mainly focused on hacking,
it may soon corrupt the entire process of e-commerce, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Transactions like electronic fund transfer, credit and debit
card transactions may face serious jeopardy in the hands of such "
digitally corrupt" people, he said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Pandora's Box on cyber-crime was opened only
recently when a wholesale hacking was detected in one of the
leading Internet service provider (ISP) firms -- Brac Bdmail.
</P>
<P>
"This exposed our vulnerability in the area of cyber-rights
protection and total lack of legal provisions for combating the
menace," said an insider of ISP.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, all the ISPs recently met the Adviser of the
National Committee on Software Exports Jamilur Reza Choudhury and
the topic was discussed.
</P>
<P>
The committee has already recommended the government work out
the modalities for putting timely cyber-laws in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
