<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Coastal People live in Tension During Cyclones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Ten million people in the coastal
areas of Bangladesh are living in tension during cyclones and
tidal surges, as only one taka (two U.S. cents) is being spent per
head for saving the lives and properties of the people from these
natural disasters, the official Bangladesh News Agency reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
About 11 million people have been living in 11 coastal
districts of the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There are 1,841 cyclone shelters in the coastal areas of the
districts for about 1.3 million of people only. For the safety of
the people, 3,000 cyclone shelters are needed in the areas.
</P>
<P>
There are 32,904 volunteers of the Red Crescent Society of
Bangladesh in the coastal areas and they are working in 2,742
units of the society.
</P>
<P>
Besides, at least 4,000 fishermen and 1,200 students have been
trained up for facing the calamities during the disasters. The Red
Crescent Society will depend on the volunteers as it has an
insufficient number of workers.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998-99 fiscal year, 11.7 million taka (234,000 U.S.
dollars) was approved by the government for the Red Crescent
society. It means that only one taka is being spent per head of
the coastal people who are facing natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The coastal people need more cyclone shelters, modern equipment,
sirens for awareness and transport for easy transfer of the people
of the coastal belts, the report stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
