<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom to Launch Videophone Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- "Face-to-face" telephone
conversations will soon become commonplace in China as China
Telecom is to offer videophone and long-distance video-
conferencing services throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The program will be first introduced into the Shenzhen Special
Economic Zone, according to today's Business Weekly.
</P>
<P>
While now the main obstacle to the development of videophone
services is the phone's high price for ordinary households, said
Zhou Jiajian, an official with Shenzhen Shenda Telephone Co. Ltd.,
at the ongoing China's First Videophone and Long-distance
Conferencing Equipment Exhibition in Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
A videophone will cost about 4,000 yuan (about 480 U.S. dollars)
to 6,000 yuan, which is much higher than a television or a washing
machine.
</P>
<P>
However, the price is expected to fall dramatically once the
videophone becomes the target of mass production. And with the
improvement of manufacturing technology, the retail price will be
likely to drop to some 2,200 yuan, said Huang Donglin, an expert
on videophone and long-distance videoconferencing programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
