<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurers Dabble in Hi-Tech Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China's insurance companies have
begun to dabble in the hi-tech computer insurance field, while no
company has yet dared to handle complicated computer insurance
designed to hedge losses stemming from hacker damage and computer
viruses.
</P>
<P>
China has seen a surge in the number of its computer users in
recent years, and the overall assets of the computer industry in
China amounted to 300 billion yuan (about 36 billion U.S. dollars)
by April last year, according to the statistics from the country's
largest non-life insurer, the People's Insurance Company of China
(PICC).
</P>
<P>
PICC began to offer computer insurance products in 1995 on a
trial basis. Encouraged by past success, it decided recently to
offer the insurance nationwide through its outlets, said today's
Business Weekly.
</P>
<P>
Policyholders can be compensated by PICC if damage occurs to
computer hardware or if they have to copy their data because of
disasters including fires, explosions, pipeline breakages,
thunderstorms, hurricanes, or robberies.
</P>
<P>
Computer users have shown great enthusiasm for new products
with booming sales in Shanghai and Zhejiang, Guangdong, Liaoning
provinces since its debut. "Profits of the new product are fairly
high and we expect it to become a new growth sector in PICC," said
a managing staff with PICC.
</P>
<P>
According to related market surveys, repair fees of computers
during the past two years have been about 2 percent to 5 percent
of a computer's purchase price. And some well-known computer
manufacturers even have to spend the equivalent of 10 percent to
16 percent of their turnover from sales every year to back their
products.
</P>
<P>
While, with the popularization of computers, computer risks
have increased as well in recent years. The security of
computerized data is threatened by attacks from viruses and
hackers, and PICC has listed them as liability-free clauses as
these are hard to control.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, established overseas insurers have been engaged in
the hacker and virus insurance business for years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
