<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: More Tourism Attractions Developed in HK (1)  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The green countryside and cultural
heritage of Hong Kong are becoming new tourist attractions for its
tens of thousands of travelers, who accept the city not just as a
world class metropolis known for shopping and dining experiences.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA)
in 1999 found that some 20 percent of the visitors to Hong Kong
expressed interest in taking part in hiking and other outdoor
activities in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Tourists often have the wrong impression that Hong Kong is a
city without much country. Actually, more than 40 percent of Hong
Kong's land is protected in 23 country and marine parks that are
home to a wide variety of flora and fauna," said HKTA executive
director Amy Chan recently.
</P>
<P>
She told Xinhua that some species, such as the Romer's tree
frog, are found nowhere else in the world, while the blackfaced
spoonbill, one of the rarest birds, makes the Mai Po wetland a
halfway house on their winter migration.
</P>
<P>
"Green tourism may not be something the world immediately
associates with Hong Kong, but there is no reason why not," said
Chan. "Our hiking trails are not only gloriously beautiful, but
also uniquely accessible, most being within an hour's journey by
public transport from just about anywhere."
</P>
<P>
To develop this new travel vogue, the HKTA published a new
guidebook, Exploring Hong Kong's Countryside -- A Visitor's
Companion, in cooperation with the Agriculture, Fisheries and
Conservation Department of Hong Kong last year.
</P>
<P>
"It is a passport to our rich natural heritage which I hope
will encourage both tourists and locals alike to explore our
magnificent countryside -- and by doing so, learn to respect the
environment that we all have a duty to help protect," said Chan. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: More Tourist Attractions Developed in HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The HKTA's efforts to diversify tourist attractions have got
support from the government. Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), stressed the
sustainable development of tourism and its promotion as an
important part of the strategy.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement we reached with Walt Disney Company for the
development of Hong Kong Disneyland is one manifestation of this
goal. The international theme park, which is due to open in 2005,
will help to keep Hong Kong as a key destination on the global
tourism map," said Tung recently.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Disney theme park, the Hong Kong SAR government has
invited expression of interest in the construction and operation
of a scenic cable car system to link up the new airport with the
Giant Buddha on Lantau Island.
</P>
<P>
The feasibility study on a proposed Fisherman's Wharf
development in the traditional fishing village is near completion.
To capitalize on the growing interest of eco-tourism, Hong Kong
will soon begin building an International Wetland Park adjacent to
Mai Po Marshes in the New Territories which is already an
internationally recognized wildlife conservation site.
</P>
<P>
Heritage and culture, another important aspect of Hong Kong's
tourist attractions, have received priority in the government
blueprint for tourism development. The Heritage Tourism Task Force
(HTTF), chaired by the HKTA, has been established to promote Hong
Kong's distinctive heritage.
</P>
<P>
"The HKTA's strategy for promotion has in the past focused on
ensuring that our markets are aware of the existence and
accessibility of our many heritage sites," said Chan.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, 23 percent of all visitors to Hong Kong expressed
interest in this area, she said, noting that there have been very
significant increases in the level of interest in heritage
activities over the past few years, compared to the only 7.6
percent of all visitors interested in such activities in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Some of the traditional Chinese festivals, such as the Birthday
of Goddess of the Sea recently, are most popular events for
tourists nowadays. Dragon Boat racing that takes place in June
during the Tuen Ng Festival has become one of Hong Kong's most
exciting and most loved spectacles.
</P>
<P>
"Now the main objective is developing more local awareness and
appreciation of our significant past. Hong Kong has much of which
to be proud and much that is worth preserving for generations to
come," said Chan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
