<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Seeks Data from Delhi for Flood Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has asked India to provide
available data on water level of rivers in the upper catchment
areas to facilitate early flood warning, The Daily Star reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We have already requested the Indian Water Resources Ministry
to supply us available figures on the state of rivers which flow
from the upper reaches to Bangladesh's deltaic region," Khalilur
Rahman, chairman of the Joint Rivers Commission, told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
A total of 54 rivers flow from India into the Bay of Bengal
through Bangladesh. A treaty on sharing Ganges water was signed
between the two countries on December 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
"If we get prior information about water level in the upper
catchment areas, we will be able to calculate the movement and
expected level of water in the downstream more accurately," said
the expert.
</P>
<P>
He said information on flow of water will enhance the flood
forecasting ability by increasing the lead time from present 48
hours to at least 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the country suffered its worst floods in a century.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the pattern of water flow in rivers can be
predicted to a great extent if data and information are exchanged
between the two countries regularly.
</P>
<P>
But Bangladesh now has no access to data monitored by India on
other common rivers except the Ganges, said the experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
