<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Inflation Rate Reaches 70-Week High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- India's inflation rate reached a
70-week high of 6.10 percent for the week ended April 22 on
account of a sharp increase in electricity tariffs during the week,
an official release said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was the highest since December 19, 1998, when a 6.13
percent inflation rate was recorded, said the release.
</P>
<P>
During the week ended April 22, there was a 15 percent rise in
electricity tariffs across the country, which led to the sharp
increase in inflation, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The 6.10 percent rate was 0.55 percentage points up from the
previous week, while the inflation rate for the corresponding week
of last year was merely 3.86 percent, it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the index for all commodities also
rose sharply by 0.8 percent during the week ended April 22 to 151.
4 from 150.2 the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
