<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Brunei Agree to Develop Business Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Brunei have agreed to
develop, together with Malaysia, business and industrial centers
around the border areas of the three countries on Borneo island,
leading newspapers reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached here Saturday during a meeting
between Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid and visiting Brunei
Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah, according to the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab said after the meeting
that joint economic activities would be able to reduce social
tensions caused partly by the huge economic gap among the people
living in the area.
</P>
<P>
"Our people near the border, for instance, see Bruneians
driving Mercedes while they themselves only drive bullock carts.
So in eliminating the jealousy, investment must be boosted around
the borders," he said.
</P>
<P>
The sultan arrived in Jakarta on Friday evening for a two-day
working visit, as a courtesy following Wahid's stopover in Bandar
Sri Begawan, capital of Brunei, on February 27.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two leaders also discussed the latest
developments in Indonesia's troubled provinces of Aceh, Maluku and
North Maluku.
</P>
<P>
Wahid assured his guest that the Aceh problem would be solved
soon through the signing of a note of understanding between the
central government and the Free Aceh Movement (GAM) in Geneva next
week.
</P>
<P>
"The signing in Geneva will become a starting point toward
peace for Aceh people. And the sultan was happy to obtain the
explanation," said Alwi.
</P>
<P>
The sultan promised to step up investment in Indonesia. He also
offered scholarships for Indonesian students who want to study in
the oil industry in Brunei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
