<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Reaches 27 in Indonesia's Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from a powerful
earthquake that caused widespread damage in the eastern province
of Central Sulawesi, Indonesia, grew to 27 on Saturday, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Musdar Amin, secretary to the emergency post in Banggai regency,
the worst hit area, said Saturday in Makassar, South Sulawesi,
that more than 153 people were seriously injured. "Forty-three of
them are in critical condition," reports reaching here Sunday said.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said they expected the death toll to grow, as
the quake caused a small tsunami tidal wave that struck some of
the outlying islands.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake measuring 6.5 on the Richter scale jolted the
Banggai islands on Thursday. The epicenter of the quake was in the
Peleng strait, some 2,000 kilometers northeast of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Local officials estimated that about 80 percent of the
buildings on Banggai islands were damaged.
</P>
<P>
The emergency post also recorded that more than 250 government
offices, 64 churches, 92 mosques, 182 schools, 15 health centers
and approximately 11,000 residential houses were damaged by the
quake.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a total of 148 roads and 15 bridges were destroyed,
Musdar said, adding that aftershocks upset the residents on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorology and Geophysics Agency in Makassar have recorded
at least 200 aftershocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
