<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Army Frees 110 Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A total of 110 hostages kidnapped by
a Colombian guerrilla group were released Saturday by a Colombian
military force in a surprise operation.
</P>
<P>
The National Liberation Army (ELN) kidnapped the 110 people on
a road of the southern department of El Cauca at 05:30 local time
Saturday after the guerrilla group set up a checkpoint near the
city of Timbio, detouring tourists-loaded buses toward a
mountainous zone, army communications chief Colonel Paulino
Coronado said.
</P>
<P>
Two guerrilla members were killed and two others were seized
during the raid carried out by the military force. All of the
abducted people were free unhurt, the colonel said.
</P>
<P>
The ELN guerrilla and the government have been arranging the
details for the start of the peace talks suspended more than one
year ago, when President Andres Pastrana refused to demilitarize a
region in the north of the country to turn it into the scenario
for the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Residents of three cities in the northern departments or
provinces of Antioquia and Bolivar, where the military forces
would be withdrawn for negotiations with the ELN, have protested
against the withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
