<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Population Goal for Next Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China will control its population to
within 1.4 billion by the end of 2010, according to a decision on
population and family planning issued by the Chinese Communist
Party Central Committee and the State Council on March 2.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, China will try to keep the average
population birth rate under 1.5 percent a year, according to the
decision. The populations in the Hong Kong and Macao special
administrative regions and in Taiwan Province are not included in
the project.
</P>
<P>
China will also work to improve the health of newborns, balance
the proportion of baby girls and boys in the total number of
newborns, and provide better reproductive health care services.
</P>
<P>
An improved family planning system will also be created
featuring more effective management, administrative measures, and
laws.
</P>
<P>
The decision cited several principles which will help realize
the population goal in the next decade. The population growth
should be coordinated with the economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The country will continue to encourage marriage and
childbearing at later ages and call for "one child per couple,"
while some couples will be allowed to have a second child in
accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
People from ethnic minority groups should also follow the
family planning policy. But the specific regulations for them will
be issued by the governments of provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
Other principles include involving all of society in promoting
family planning and solving the population problem, combining
state rules with people's will, and improving people's life and
education through family planning services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Population Control System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China will build a more complete
control system and create a better environment through state
policies to promote population and family planning work, according
to a decision issued by the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee and the State Council on March 2.
</P>
<P>
The decision called on governments and departments at all
levels to consider the best interests of the planning work when
they set regulations and reform measures concerning land,
enterprises, health care, social security, household register,
labor, education and finance.
</P>
<P>
The country will speed up the legislative work on population
and family planning and improve the laws governing family planning,
the decision said.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels should help rural families which
follow the family planning policy to increase their income, solve
problems, and improve their social and economic status.
</P>
<P>
Rural areas should continue to practice the principle that the
area of a family's tilth will not be affected by the increase or
reduction of its population. And those families who violate
family planning regulations should be fined for the additional
children they bear.
</P>
<P>
One-child families in urban areas are to receive the one-child
bonus, and parents can apply for government subsidies after
retirement. Rural families which practice family planning,
especially those only having girls, will enjoy favorable treatment
in income distribution, public welfare and contracting of land.
</P>
<P>
China will reform the social security system so that it will
provide pensions for parents who practiced family planning,
according to the decision.
</P>
<P>
In urban areas, the pension insurance, basic health care
insurance, social welfare and other kinds of social security
systems will be available, while in rural areas, local governments
will form a pension system for one-child and two-daughter families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthens Family Planning Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China will involve all corners of
society to promote the country's family planning work, according
to a decision issued by the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee and the State Council On March 2.
</P>
<P>
The decision said that communities should introduce population
and family planning work into their management and service. In
rural areas, the work will be launched by village committees while
in urban areas, street and neighborhood committees should be
responsible for it.
</P>
<P>
Local governments of areas where transient populations live
should take the major share of responsibility for their family
planning, and provide the migrants with necessary services.
</P>
<P>
Departments of information, education, science and technology,
and culture should play active roles in spreading knowledge about
population and family planning and create a better social
environment for family planning, the decision said.
</P>
<P>
Family planning and health care departments will cooperate to
provide services for birth control and other reproductive health
care needs. And more safe, effective and proper contraceptive
methods should be available for women of childbearing age.
</P>
<P>
The development and promotion of new technology and new
products for contraception, birth control, prenatal and postnatal
care should be encouraged, according to the decision.
</P>
<P>
China will also expand international cooperation and exchanges
in population and family planning to study and introduce advanced
experience and methods in the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
