<HEADLINE> Security Council Begins Closed Meeting on Horn of Africa, Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
began to convene an emergent meeting on Sunday afternoon to
discuss the collapsed peace talks between Ethiopia and Eritrea and
be briefed on the latest developments in Sierra Leone, where a
large number of U.N. peacekeepers were taken hostage by rebels, U.
N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting started at around 3:30 p.m. EST.
Ethiopia and Eritrea, which have been engaged in a border conflict
for two years, blamed each other for the breakdown of talks Friday
in the Algerian capital of Algiers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bernard Miyet, the U.N. under-secretary-general for
peacekeeping, decided to fly to Sierra Leone to boost the morale
of U.N. troops and join the political talks underway on the
hundreds of U.N. peacekeepers still held by rebels in the West
African country, the U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said.
</P>
<P>
"He is to boost the morale of troops in the wake of the
devastating events of the last few days and to help the political
process underway to try to resolve the matter of the hostages
peacefully," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
In Sierra Leone, rebels from the Revolutionary United Fronted
were battling U.N. peacekeepers in the interior of the West
African country while U.N. troops were reported mobilizing for
action in the nation's capital of Freetown. The rebels have taken
at least 300 U.N. peacekeepers hostage over the last week, with
another 200 missing.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeepers are mainly from Zambia, India,Kenya and
Nigeria and were dispatched to the West African country to monitor
a peace accord signed last July to end the nine-year civil war in
the country.  
</P>
