<HEADLINE> Britain Warns Its Citizens to Leave Sierr </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The British government on Sunday
decided to reduce its diplomatic support staff in Sierra Leone and
warned its nationals to leave the Western African country because
of the deteriorating security situation.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided that we will reduce our diplomatic staff in
Sierra Leone and we are advising British nationals with no
essential reasons for remaining to leave," said Foreign Minister
Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
The move comes after the abduction of several hundred members
of the United Nations peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, the United States advised its citizens to leave,
saying the international airport in Freetown, the capital city of
Sierra Leone, was liable to close without warning.
</P>
<P>
Britain is also sending troops and warships to Sierra Leone as
a"precautionary measure" to help Britons trapped there.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Defense said the force being sent to that
region comprised a paratroop battalion, a frigate, a helicopter
carrier and three support vessels.
</P>
<P>
In Sierra Leone, fighting has resumed in breach of a 1999 peace
accord which Britain helped to broker.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations accused rebel forces of holding some 300 of
its peace-keepers and civilian staff hostage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
