<HEADLINE> Update: Britain sends Taskforce to Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain is on Sunday sending a
battalion of paratroops and five warships to West Africa to help
Britons who may need to be airlifted from violence in Sierra Leone
because of the deteriorating security situation.
</P>
<P>
About 700-800 soldiers including support staff, as well as a
helicopter carrier, a frigate and three support ships are to be
deployed, it was announced in London.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Ministry of Defense stressed that the
deployments were "precautionary measures to ensure that we are
best placed to respond quickly to safeguard the security of
British nationals, if that becomes necessary".
</P>
<P>
That deployment follows a similar decision by the United States
to provide helicopters to fly its nationals out of Sierra Leone,
where fighting has resumed in breach of a 1999 peace accord which
Britain helped to broker.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Office spokesman said the decision had been taken to
move key military assets to Senegal, a country near Sierra Leone,
"as a precautionary measure should an evacuation of British
nationals from Sierra Leone be required."
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Sunday, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Britain
was cutting the number of non-essential staff in its Sierra Leone
embassy and urging its nationals to leave.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided that we will reduce our diplomatic staff in
Sierra Leone and we are advising British nationals with no
essential reasons for remaining to leave," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
These actions came after the abduction of several hundred
members of the United Nations peacekeeping force in that Western
African country.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations accused rebel forces in Sierra Leone of
holding some 300 of its peacekeepers and civilian staff hostage.
</P>
<P>
Cook, speaking at a meeting of European Union foreign ministers
in Portugal's Azores Islands, said renewed fighting underlined the
need for U.N. peacekeeping forces to be brought up to full
strength as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has around 8,700 troops in Sierra Leone,due
to reach its full strength of 11,000 by July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
