<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Sends Mission to Horn of Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Sunday decided to authorize its Mission to the Democratic Republic
of Congo to visit Ethiopia and Eritrea on Monday to urge the two
neighboring African countries to refrain from resorting to force
and further hostilities.
</P>
<P>
The decision was adopted at the end of an emergency meeting
here on Sunday afternoon after the indirect peace talks between
Ethiopia and Eritrea broke in Algiers, capital of Algeria, Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The Mission will travel to Addis Ababa and Asmara to meet
with the Government of Ethiopia and the Government of Eritrea,"
the Security Council said in a press handout.
</P>
<P>
"The Mission, acting on the basis of relevant Security Council
decisions, will express in the strongest possible terms the
Council's support for the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
peace process, for its current Chair Algeria, and for their
ongoing efforts to achieve a negotiated settlement to this
conflict," the Council said.
</P>
<P>
"This Mission will urge strongly both parties to refrain from
resorting to force and further hostilities, and to commit
immediately, seriously and without precondition to negotiations to
achieve final consolidated technical arrangements for
implementation of the OAU Framework Agreement and its Modalities
for Implementation," said the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The two countries went to war in May 1998 over their frontier,
which has not been demarcated since Eritrea gained independence
from Ethiopia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Both Eritrea and Ethiopia have accepted a framework peace
agreement and a broad implementation strategy drafted by the OAU,
but differences existed between the two countries over the
technical arrangement for the implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000507.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Considers A Field Mission to Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Sunday studied the possibility to send another field mission to
Sierra Leone in order to secure the quick settlement to the
hostage crisis in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by the president of the Security
Council, Wang Yingfan of China, at the end of an emergency meeting
of the 15-member body.
</P>
<P>
The Council began to convene an emergent meeting on Sunday
afternoon to discuss the collapsed peace talks between Ethiopia
and Eritrea and be briefed on the latest developments in Sierra
Leone, where a large number of U.N. peacekeepers were taken
hostage by rebels.
</P>
<P>
"We explored the possibility whether the Security Council
could send another field mission (to Sierra Leone), like (what) we
did in Kosovo, and now in the DRC (the Democratic Republic of
Congo)," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has sent Bernard Miyet, the
U.N. under-secretary-general for peacekeeping, to Sierra Leone,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U.N. spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said that Miyet is
flying to Sierra Leone to boost the morale of U.N. troops and join
the political talks underway on the hundreds of U.N. peacekeepers
still held by rebels in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
"He is to boost the morale of troops in the wake of the
devastating events of the last few days and to help the political
process underway to try to resolve the matter of the hostages
peacefully," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
In Sierra Leone, rebels from the Revolutionary United Fronted
were battling U.N. peacekeepers in the interior of the West
African country while U.N. troops were reported mobilizing for
action in the nation's capital of Freetown. The rebels have taken
at least 300 U.N. peacekeepers hostage over the last week, with
another 200 missing.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeepers are mainly from Zambia, India,Kenya and
Nigeria and were dispatched to the West African country to monitor
a peace accord signed last July to end the nine-year civil war in
the country.  
</P>
